SUMMARY:Twitty & Lynn
DESCRIPTION:There‚Äôs never been a more dynamic country music duo than Conway Twitty and Loretta Lynn, and now the torch has been passed to the next generation: Tayla Lynn and Tre Twitty. Twitty & Lynn is a must-see show that delivers their iconic grandparents‚Äô super hits, and will make a stop at the Brown County Music Center in Nashville, Ind., on Saturday, August 15, 2026.\nThere‚Äôs a moment right at the very beginning of any Twitty & Lynn show that affords country music fans the chance to look back in time. Just after the band has played the signature intro to ‚ÄúLouisiana Woman, Mississippi Man,‚Äù Tre Twitty and Tayla Lynn shoot each other a glance that summons the electrifying chemistry of their grandparents: Tre is the grandson of Conway Twitty, Tayla is the granddaughter of Loretta Lynn.\nBut Twitty & Lynn ‚Äî and their internationally popular show ‚ÄúA Salute to Conway & Loretta‚Äù ‚Äî aren‚Äôt impersonators. Tre doesn‚Äôt groom Seventies sideburns and perm his hair; Tayla doesn‚Äôt mimic her grandmother‚Äôs mannerisms. Rather, they are onstage celebrating country music, the lost art of duet singing, and the two beloved icons they refer to as ‚ÄúPoppy‚Äù and ‚ÄúMemaw.‚Äù\nThe duo credits their show‚Äôs popularity to the timeless songs of Conway and Loretta ‚Äî duets like ‚ÄúAfter the Fire Is Gone‚Äù and ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre the Reason Our Kids Are Ugly‚Äù are all in the set, along with Conway and Loretta solo hits like ‚ÄúHello, Darlin‚Äô‚Äù and ‚ÄúCoal Miner‚Äôs Daughter.‚Äù But they‚Äôre also giving audiences a chance to relive a moment in time that ended far too soon: Conway and Loretta stopped touring together full-time in 1981, and Conway died in 1993. ‚ÄúConway has been gone 30 years,‚Äù Tre says. ‚ÄúHad Poppy lived, I think there would have been a great second act for him and Loretta. There‚Äôs a lot of people that wanted to see that, and we‚Äôre able to let them hear those songs and stories again.‚Äù\n
URL:https://browncounty.com/events/twitty-lynn-2/
